{"timestamp": "2025-11-29 17:13:36.883702", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — SDN spine–leaf topology\nSummary\n- Network health: Partial outage. Intra-leaf (hosts on the same leaf) connectivity on leaf_2 is healthy; inter-leaf L2 connectivity (traffic between hosts attached to different leaf switches) is broken.\n- Primary anomaly: The spine switch (spine_1) is forwarding packets back out the ingress port instead of forwarding them to the other leaf. This prevents leaf_1 ↔ leaf_2 traffic.\n- Likely root cause: Incorrect OpenFlow rules installed on spine_1 (controller-installs or flow programming bug) that output to the same port the packet arrived on (hairpin), so spine is not forwarding between leaf ports.\n\nEvidence and findings (collected outputs)\n1) Reachability summary (ping matrix)\n- host_1_1 -> host_2_1 (10.0.0.3): 4 TX, 0 RX, 100% loss, status \"down\"\n- host_1_1 -> host_2_2 (10.0.0.4): 4 TX, 0 RX, 100% loss, status \"down\"\n- host_2_2 -> host_2_1: 4 TX, 4 RX, 0% loss, status \"ok\"\nInterpretation: Hosts on leaf_2 (10.0.0.3 & 10.0.0.4) can reach each other, but host_1_1 (on leaf_1) cannot reach hosts on leaf_2.\n\n2) Host network config (all hosts)\n- host_1_1: 10.0.0.1/24, eth0 UP\n- host_1_2: 10.0.0.2/24, eth0 UP\n- host_2_1: 10.0.0.3/24, eth0 UP\n- host_2_2: 10.0.0.4/24, eth0 UP\nInterpretation: IP addressing and local link state on host NICs are normal.\n\n3) OVS bridge and port status\n- leaf_1: Bridge exists and controller tcp:20.0.0.100:6633 is_connected: true. Ports eth0, eth1, eth2 present. LOCAL(leaf_1) interface state: PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN.\n- leaf_2: Bridge exists and controller connected. Ports eth0, eth1, eth2 present. LOCAL(leaf_2) interface state: PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN.\n- spine_1: Bridge exists and controller connected. Ports eth0 (port 1) and eth1 (port 2) state: LIVE. LOCAL(spine_1) state: LINK_DOWN.\nInterpretation: Bridges are present and controller connection appears up, but the internal LOCAL port on each OVS bridge shows LINK_DOWN (this is the bridge's internal netdev; not necessarily fatal for data-plane but noteworthy).\n\n4) OpenFlow flow tables (OF1.3)\n- leaf_1 (bridge leaf_1) flows (excerpt):\n  - table=0, in_port=2 actions=output:2\n  - table=0, in_port=1,dl_src=4e:1c:36:6f:5c:fd,dl_dst=12:d6:20:ed:ee:6e actions=output:3\n  - table=0, in_port=1,dl_src=4e:1c:36:6f:5c:fd,dl_dst=d6:88:47:21:e0:b6 actions=output:3\n  (port mapping: 1=eth0, 2=eth1, 3=eth2)\n  Interpretation: leaf_1 is forwarding host->spine on eth2 for known dst MACs (expected).\n\n- leaf_2 flows (excerpt):\n  - in_port=1,dl_src=d6:88:47:21:e0:b6,dl_dst=12:d6:20:ed:ee:6e actions=output:2\n  - in_port=2,dl_src=12:d6:20:ed:ee:6e,dl_dst=d6:88:47:21:e0:b6 actions=output:1\n  (port mapping: 1=eth0, 2=eth1, 3=eth2)\n  Interpretation: leaf_2 has symmetric flows between its hosts (1↔2) — local switching works.\n\n- spine_1 flows (excerpt):\n  - table=0, in_port=1 actions=output:1\n  (port mapping: 1=eth0 (to leaf_1), 2=eth1 (to leaf_2))\n  Interpretation: spine_1 has a flow that, when a packet arrives on port 1, outputs it back to port 1 (same port). That is incorrect for inter-leaf forwarding and will prevent traffic from leaf_1 being delivered to leaf_2 (should be output:2).\n\n5) OFPT_PORT_DESC from ovs-ofctl show\n- spine_1: port1 (eth0) state LIVE, port2 (eth1) state LIVE — physical links appear up.\n- leaf_1 and leaf_2: port descriptions show eth ports LIVE as well.\nInterpretation: physical connectivity between spine and leaves looks up; data-plane problem is at flow/action level.\n\nSynthesis / Analysis\n- Symptom: Hosts on the same leaf (leaf_2) can communicate; hosts across different leaves cannot. Packets from leaf_1 to leaf_2 are being forwarded from leaf_1 to the spine (leaf_1 flows forward to its eth2), but spine_1 is not forwarding those packets to the eth connected to leaf_2 — instead it outputs packets back to the same ingress port (in_port=1 → output:1).\n- Localized faulty component: spine_1 (the spine OVS instance) flow table contains incorrect forwarding action(s) that create a hairpin; this prevents inter-leaf traffic.\n- Controller relationship: The bridges report they are connected to the controller (controller: tcp:20.0.0.100:6633 is_connected: true). Because the flow entries are present (and incorrect) on spine_1, the controller likely installed those wrong flows or there is a controller-app bug producing wrong actions. The presence of LOCAL port LINK_DOWN is noted but not the primary cause evidenced here (physical links to leaves are LIVE).\n- Additional oddities: leaf bridges show their LOCAL port LINK_DOWN. This is an observation that may be relevant to controller-bridge integration or management plane, but the key functional failure is the spine's mis-forwarding flow.\n\nRoot-cause hypothesis (most likely)\n- The SDN controller (or the flow-programming logic) installed incorrect flows on spine_1 such that packets arriving from leaf_1 are output to the same port (in_port → output: same_port) instead of being forwarded to the other leaf port. This results in a broken inter-leaf data path. The controller is reachable (bridges report connected), but programmatic forwarding state is incorrect.\n\nImpact / scope\n- Affected traffic: Any L2 traffic that must traverse spine_1 between leaf_1 and leaf_2 (i.e., host_1_x <-> host_2_x) — currently failing.\n- Not affected / working: Local L2 on leaf_2 (host_2_1 ↔ host_2_2) — confirmed OK.\n\nRelevant artifacts (key excerpts)\n- Reachability: host_1_1 -> host_2_* 100% loss; host_2_2 -> host_2_1 OK.\n- spine_1 flows: \"table=0, n_packets=22, n_bytes=1624, reset_counts in_port=1 actions=output:1\" — shows the problematic in_port→output mapping.\n\nNotes (observations that may be helpful later)\n- The controllers are connected to all bridges (controller is_connected: true), so the issue is not (only) a controller disconnect.\n- The internal LOCAL ports of the OVS bridges show PORT_DOWN / LINK_DOWN; that is usually the bridge’s local interface, and while unusual it does not explain the symmetric wrong action on the spine (the explicit flow action is the proximate cause).\n- Flow entries on leaves show forwarding to the spine for remote MACs — leaf->spine behavior is as expected; spine should map dst MAC to the correct leaf port but currently it does not.\n\nConclusion\n- There is a clear data-plane anomaly: spine_1 is not forwarding traffic between leaf ports due to incorrect flow actions (packets are output back to their ingress port). This causes inter-leaf connectivity to fail while intra-leaf switching (at least on leaf_2) remains functional.\n- The most likely root cause is incorrect flow programming on spine_1 (controller-installed flow entries or controller application bug). The bridging/control-plane connection exists, so investigate flow-programming logic or controller behavior that results in in_port→output:same_port rules on spine_1.\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- Show full flow tables for all switches, include port-to-neighbor mapping summary, or\n- Query the controller (if accessible) or retrieve more flow-change timestamps to see when those incorrect rules were installed.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 13225, "output_tokens": 3817, "total_tokens": 17042, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 12800}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1856}}}
